In the case of some consonants the passage is closed at a given point, e. g. at the lips inp, l; at the teeth in t, d; at the palate in k, g, while the nose passage is closed by the bottom of the soft palate. In the case of other consonants the passage is not closed but only narrowed, and the breath sounds against the narrow walls, as in s, s, ch, &c The nose channel is left open in pronouncing n, m.

In the case of vowels the breath is not checlred or closely narrowed at a given point, but passes freely through the mouth passage. 'With each different vowel-sound the mouth passage assumes, it is true, a different form which modifies the sound, but there is no check or hindrance to the free issue of the sound, nor audible friction after the breath has been vocalised by the vibration of the vocal chorda.
